         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot Garden ¶ 21/9/66 ¶  ¶ I rejoyced, dear Prof Balfour, to see the experiment of transmitting plants in calico-covered Cases attended with such perfect success, ¶  &amp; am grateful that our in...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">66.09.21</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To John Balfour</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh, J. H. Balfour correspondence, vol. X, no. 270.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne bot Garden</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">21/9/66</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I rejoyced, dear Prof Balfour, to see the experiment of transmitting plants in calico-covered Cases attended with such perfect success,<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Transactions of the Botanical Society</seg>. <seg style="font-style: italic; ">of Edinburgh</seg>, vol. 8 (1866), pp. 482-4. Proceedings of 14 June 1866; for details see notes to M to J Hooker, 14 September 1866.</p>
               </note> &amp; am grateful that our intelligent friendly Dr Madden<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Henry Madden. <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Swiftsure</seg>, on which Madden returned to the United Kingdom, cleared out of Melbourne on 21 February 1866 (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Argus</seg>, 22 February 1866, p. 4).</p>
               </note> bestowed so much friendly care on the experiment. I will bring these cases now frequently into transit.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am now preparing a large collection of terrestrial orchids melanthaceous and liliaceous plants for transmission to the coldhouses of Kew &amp; Edinburgh &amp; trust you will cause any species new to Europe to be figured in some periodical. The interchange of these lovely plants is attended with no real difficulty nor do I think that by care the plants will be lost again.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have also tubers of the charming large flowered <name key="Drosera">Drosera</name>e secured.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>By excavations during the last dry season I have reclaimed a tract of several acres of previously inundated land in the Lake of my garden &amp; transformed it into a pleasure forest. What would be delightful is this, if of Trientalis, <name key="Majanthemum">Majanthemum</name>, <name key="Lysimachia%20vulgaris">Lysimachia vulgaris</name>, L. thyrsiflora, <name key="Circaea">Circaea</name>e, [<name key="Gentiana">Gentiana</name>e]<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">editorial addition</seg> — word partly obscured.</p>
               </note>, Parnassia, and any other forest or moor plant seeds in some <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">quantity</hi>
               </seg> could be secured during the excursions you are instituting.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">For the role of Balfour's long excursions see Allen (2000), p. 354, and Balfour (1908).</p>
               </note> These lovely plants could undoubtedly all be rendered wild here. I have planted into this pleasure forest 200 large fern trees, many fifty years old, also Xanthorrhoeae of great age &amp; hight, which move perfectly as well as Zamiae stems.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am immodest enough to make an other request; could not in a little water-tight box or tub roots of Iris Pseudacorus, Stratiotes aloides, <name key="Butomus%20umbellatus">Butomus umbellatus</name>, Hottonia palustris, Sagittaria sagittifolia and other noble water plants and roots (or seeds?) of <name key="Menyanthes%20trifoliata">Menyanthes trifoliata</name>, <name key="Lysimachia%20thyrsiflora%20">Lysimachia thyrsiflora </name>Utricularia &amp;c and other swamp plants be transmitted, when some intelligent passenger proceeds hither. <name key="Acorus">Acorus</name>
               <name key="Calamus">Calamus</name>, <name key="Nuphar%20luteum">Nuphar luteum</name> &amp; Nymphaea alba I have, and <name key="Lythrum">Lythrum</name>
               <name key="Salicaria">Salicaria</name> is indigenous.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Seeds of Lychnis flos-Cuculi would be also nice.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I could in exchange send you roots of Ottelia ovalifolia, Villarsia parnassifolia &amp;c &amp;c &amp;c</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Have you <name key="Manihot">Manihot</name> in cultivation. As yet this important plant has not reached Australia.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M had been asking for <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Manihot">Manihot</name>
                     </seg> plants since at least M to J. Hooker, 25 December 1865) in this edition as 65-12-25e), and in M to C. von Martius, 25 Decenber 1865 (in this edition as 65-12-25b), he thanked von Martius for advice and warnings about its potential toxicity. In M to J. Hooker 25 October 1866 (in this edition as 66-10-25c), he thanked Hooker for the supply of living material.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I wished our interchanges could be more frequent, they would advance much the mutual interest of our departments.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Has your R.S. a complete set of my works? If not I will gladly complete it. I am just about finishing the 5 vol of my fragmenta.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The final parts were published in December 1866.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">your attached</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd Mueller</p>
